english:
  title: Following the Four Lovely Rhymes
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My brush lies lazy on the desk, poems unfinished.
    I wander through the eastern garden in straw sandals.
    Bees sip the flower's stamen, their fragrance drifting down the path.
    Musk deer drowse on the spring hillside, their green shadows trailing the stream.
    On the ridge tops, a thousand stalks of goji stretch long.
    Beside the rocks, ginseng leaves gather in perfect fives.
    The Buddhist temple stands desolate, worldly cares grow thin.
    Only swallows gather clay beneath the painted eaves.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'four lovely rhymes' (四佳韻) refers to a poetic form or constraint, likely involving four parallel couplets with specific rhyme schemes.
  - key: ''
    value: The progression from literary pursuits abandoned to natural observation reflects a common Daoist-influenced theme in Korean literati poetry—the retreat from society's demands into contemplative communion with nature.
  - key: ''
    value: Goji (枸杞) and ginseng (人蔘) were prized medicinal herbs in classical East Asian culture, suggesting both the garden's richness and the poet's knowledge of natural philosophy.
